_Unification/working/codex-run.log:588:    16	**KBM** runs a relationship-driven CRM out of Zendesk, with deal-level data tracked inconsistently because CRM use has been optional. When a deal closes, customer information is re-entered manually into Core for order processing, and RFPs are managed in Asana on a separate timeline that marketing only sees once a formal request is submitted. The team has internalized the cost of this fragmentation — the team's own description of the data quality is "poo in, poo out" — and has come into Orion implementation explicitly looking to make CRM use mandatory and unified. KBM's pain point is *consistency*. The discipline they want from Orion is not optional.
_Unification/working/codex-run.log:590:    18	**Pivot** runs a structured CRM out of HubSpot for opportunity management, with downstream quoting and invoicing already in NetSuite (and migrating from D365). Forecasting is exported monthly from HubSpot to Excel, weighted manually, and pivoted for executive review — accurate but lagging by days or weeks. RFPs are tracked separately in Monday.com. Pivot's organization is structured around four divisions (Enterprise, Venture, Public, Construction Solutions) with a hierarchy of executive → SVP/GM → sales operations → designers/reps. Pivot's pain point is *real-time visibility and integration*; their data discipline is already good, but the round trip through Excel costs them speed and the disconnect between CRM and downstream systems costs them margin visibility.
